title: For Sale:  Non-NFA 14" PGO Mossberg 500 Cruiser Pump-Action 12 Gauge
location: Saint Marys, PA, North Central, PA, Pennsylvania
postcontent:
Brand new in the box and only two in stock! Ready to ship, buy it today! 

Although this firearm is not restricted Federally, please check you local and state laws to ensure that this does not meet the definition of a Short-Barrel Shotgun where you live! 

A 14" Mossberg 500 that's not considered a Short-Barreled Shotgun? 

The Mossberg Cruiser (50588) that ships from Mossberg with a pistol-grip already installed and a 20" barrel is not considered a shotgun at all by ATF's definition. It is in fact just a "Firearm" because in order to fit the definition of a shotgun it must have stock to be "fired from the shoulder". 

Since it is not a shotgun it is not required to have at least an 18" barrel, the only requirement for a firearm is that it must have a length of more than 26" otherwise it would be considered an AOW. 

Each firearm will also come with copies of the ATF tech branch letters stating the ATF's opinion that these are indeed federally legal and do not require a tax stamp. 

This Mossberg 500 was built on a 500 Cruiser PGO firearm. The total length is 26 1/2". We use a complete 14" front end from a Mossberg 590A1 and a birds head grip to achieve the 26 1/2" total length. These will come in the original Mossberg 500 Crusier box for those that want to be able to prove that it has never had a stock on it.

title: For Sale:  Scarce B Grade Hi Condition A.H. Fox 12 bore
postcontent: A.H Fox B Grade, We all have heard it and many of us have said it “if only these guns could talk” Without a doubt I can tell you this one would say “let me out of this damned closet, take me hunting, taking me shooting, it’s dark in here and I want out”. S/N 172xx puts this early B grade 12 gauge dates to about 1911. It has the standard double triggers (no single available until 1913) and the fool proof extractors. Stock dimensions on the bourbon brown stock are 14” L.O.P 1 7/8 D.A.H. 2 7/8 D.A.C. Splinter forend, The wood exhibits a greater degree of grain and figure than that of the Sterlingworth or A grades and shows very nice contrast, The butt plate is the original The checkering is excellent and the side panels are factory checkered as well, there are the normal nicks and dings in a 104 year old stock that has been stuck in a closet. The Krupp number 1 weight barrels are 30” full x modified and show 97% or better original blue with a couple very small dark patches that are only noticeable under strong light. The bores are mirror bright. The case colors are 70 to 80% or better and more shows to the eye than in my pictures. The gun is all original and was well oiled when put away (an internal cleaning would be a good idea) and I believe stored muzzle down as there is very little oil staining in the wood and the accumulation of dried oil near the frames recess and rebates with a little bit or darkening of the muzzles. The engraving is excellent and is of the earlier more delicate pattern with the snipe on either side. B grade Foxes are seldom found let alone found in such high original condition and finish.

title: For Trade:  Luger 9mm - 1936
location: Tulsa and Surrounding Areas, Tulsa, Oklahoma
postcontent:
This is a very scarce early Pre-WWII German Luger manufactured by the Mauser factory. This was the first year that Germany stopped using the secret letter code markings for the year of manufacture on small arms. The chamber area is stamped "1936" and the front toggle is marked "S/42", the wartime code for the Mauser factory. The right side of the barrel extension has the early double "Eagle/63" Waffenamt proofs. It is numbered in the military fashion with the full serial number stamped on the major components and the last two digits on the various small parts. The grips are checkered walnut.
Excellent overall with 95% of the original blue finish with wear on the edges and high spots overall with blue loss on the side plate, muzzle area front frame rails with a hint of thinning on the lower grips strap. The straw colors are vivid and remain 80% intact. The grips are excellent with nice original distinct checkering on both sides, mixed with some minor handling marks. This Luger has all matching upper serial numbers and all matching lower serial numbers as is normal for a Mauser produced luger made in 1936 and referenced in the information noted in the Gun Digest article below.

The Luger Pistol
From Gun Digest Book, 11th Edition, 1957.
By: Fred A. Datig | April 20, 2009
The 1936 was the last year that Mauser used the traditional straw bluing on the small parts. Wartime production was starting up and demand required that the trigger, thumb safety, locking lever magazine release were converted to salt bluing in early 1937. Pre WWII manufacture means it was made as good as they ever were.
Beginning in 1936 Krieghoff, like Mauser, dated his products with the year of manufacture in numbers. A few examples may be encountered bearing dates of “1936″ and “1937″ which do not conform to the proper serial number range. These were pieces assembled from already numbered surplus parts at those later dates. These will have the 1936 S/42 upper all matching and all lower all matching. Some of the Mauser-made Lugers will be found bearing not only the commercial Mauser Banner but also carrying a date-stamp over the chamber. Such arms were originally intended for commercial sale, but when the German military forces demanded more Lugers than normal Mauser production could supply, pistols previously set aside for the commercial market were merely stamped with a date and accepted by the Army as regular issue weapons. In 1936 the secret code names were augmented. Mauser was assigned the code number “42″ in addition to the “S/42″ already in use.

It is not unusual, then, to find Lugers bearing the code name “S/42″ and, for example, the date “1936,” and also to encounter “42″ pieces having the same date. To add to the confusion, pieces were also produced bearing the same date, “1936,” and inscribed with the commercial Mauser Banner.
The Luger Pistol
From Gun Digest Book, 11th Edition, 1957.
By: Fred A. Datig | April 20, 2009
Editor’s Note: This is a sample article from Gun Digest Research, where you can search thousands of archived Gun Digest Annual Book archives. To learn more go to http://research.gundigest.com.
